\section{The shared I/O log}

The central piece is [[IOLog]]---a thread-safe buffer that collects
lines from all three streams in the order they arrive.
We use a single [[threading.Lock]] so that a write from stdout and a
read from stdin cannot interleave within a single line.

We cap the buffer at a configurable maximum size (default 1~MB) to
prevent a long-running program from consuming unbounded memory.
Once the cap is reached, we stop recording but continue passing data
through to the original streams---the student's program still works
normally.

<<constants>>=
MAX_IOLOG_BYTES = 1_000_000
@

\subsection{ANSI escape code stripping}
\label{ansi-stripping}

Starting with Python~3.13, the interpreter emits coloured tracebacks
using ANSI escape codes (CSI sequences such as \verb|\x1b[31m| for red
text).
These sequences are meaningful to a terminal emulator but are
unreadable noise when stored as plain text in a Git commit message.
We therefore strip all CSI sequences from captured text before
buffering it, while still passing the raw (coloured) text through to
the student's terminal unchanged.

The regex matches the standard CSI pattern: an escape character
(\verb|\x1b|), a left bracket, optional numeric parameters separated
by semicolons, and a single letter command.
This covers colours, bold/underline, cursor movement, and line
clearing---everything Python's traceback colouring produces.
We precompile the pattern into a module-level constant because
[[strip_ansi]] is called on every single write.

<<helper functions>>=
_ANSI_ESCAPE_RE = re.compile(r'\x1b\[[0-9;]*[A-Za-z]')

def strip_ansi(text):
    """Remove ANSI escape sequences from ``text``."""
    return _ANSI_ESCAPE_RE.sub('', text)
@

We need to verify two directions: that escape codes are actually
stripped (otherwise Python~3.13 tracebacks remain unreadable), and
that plain text passes through unmodified (otherwise we would corrupt
output that happens to contain bracket characters):

<<test functions>>=
def test_strip_ansi_removes_color_codes():
    colored = "\x1b[31mError\x1b[0m: something failed"
    assert strip_ansi(colored) == "Error: something failed"

def test_strip_ansi_preserves_plain_text():
    plain = "hello world\n"
    assert strip_ansi(plain) == plain

def test_strip_ansi_handles_multiple_codes():
    text = "\x1b[1m\x1b[31mBold Red\x1b[0m Normal"
    assert strip_ansi(text) == "Bold Red Normal"

def test_strip_ansi_empty_string():
    assert strip_ansi("") == ""

def test_iolog_strips_ansi_from_logged_text():
    log = IOLog()
    log.log("stderr", "\x1b[31mTraceback\x1b[0m\n")
    value = log.getvalue()
    assert "\x1b[" not in value
    assert "stderr: Traceback\n" in value
@


\subsection{The [[IOLog]] class}

<<classes>>=
class IOLog:
    """Thread-safe shared buffer for interleaved I/O logging.

    Each line is prefixed with the stream name (stdout, stderr, stdin)
    to show the origin.  The buffer is capped at ``max_bytes`` to
    prevent unbounded memory growth.
    """

    def __init__(self, max_bytes=MAX_IOLOG_BYTES):
        self.max_bytes = max_bytes
        self.lock = threading.Lock()
        self.buf = io.StringIO()
        self.size = 0
        self.truncated = False

    <<iolog methods>>
@


\subsection{Logging a line}

The [[log]] method is the core of [[IOLog]].
Before splitting the text into lines, we strip any ANSI escape
sequences (see \cref{ansi-stripping}).
This ensures the buffered log is clean plain text, while the student's
terminal still shows colours since [[StreamCapture.write]] passes
the original (unstripped) text to the real stream.

We split each write into individual lines so that the prefix appears on
every line, making the log easy to scan.
The alternative---prefixing only the first line of a multi-line
write---would produce confusing output when stdout and stderr writes
interleave mid-block.

<<iolog methods>>=
def log(self, prefix, text):
    """Log ``text`` with ``prefix`` (e.g. ``'stdout'``).

    Each line of ``text`` gets its own prefixed entry.
    ANSI escape sequences are stripped before buffering.
    If the buffer is full, further writes are silently dropped.
    """
    if not text:
        return
    text = strip_ansi(text)
    with self.lock:
        if self.truncated:
            return
        for line in text.splitlines(keepends=True):
            entry = f"{prefix}: {line}"
            if self.size + len(entry) > self.max_bytes:
                self.buf.write(
                    "\n[learnlog: I/O log truncated "
                    f"at {self.max_bytes} bytes]\n"
                )
                self.truncated = True
                return
            self.buf.write(entry)
            self.size += len(entry)
@

Let's verify the basic logging behavior---single lines, interleaved
streams, and multi-line writes:

<<test functions>>=
def test_iolog_logs_with_prefix():
    log = IOLog()
    log.log("stdout", "hello\n")
    assert log.getvalue() == "stdout: hello\n"

def test_iolog_interleaved_streams():
    log = IOLog()
    log.log("stdout", "prompt: ")
    log.log("stdin", "answer\n")
    log.log("stdout", "ok\n")
    value = log.getvalue()
    assert "stdout: prompt: " in value
    assert "stdin: answer\n" in value
    assert "stdout: ok\n" in value

def test_iolog_multiline_write():
    log = IOLog()
    log.log("stderr", "line1\nline2\n")
    value = log.getvalue()
    assert "stderr: line1\n" in value
    assert "stderr: line2\n" in value

def test_iolog_empty_write_ignored():
    log = IOLog()
    log.log("stdout", "")
    assert log.getvalue() == ""
@


\subsection{Truncation}

Once the buffer exceeds [[max_bytes]], we stop recording and append a
truncation notice.
This is a safety valve for programs that produce megabytes of output.

<<test functions>>=
def test_iolog_truncation():
    log = IOLog(max_bytes=50)
    log.log("stdout", "x" * 100 + "\n")
    value = log.getvalue()
    assert "truncated" in value
    assert log.truncated
@


\subsection{Retrieving the log}

The [[getvalue]] method returns the full buffer contents.
It acquires the lock to ensure a consistent snapshot.

<<iolog methods>>=
def getvalue(self):
    """Return the full log contents as a string."""
    with self.lock:
        return self.buf.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Thread safety}

Multiple threads may write to stdout and stderr concurrently.
We verify that concurrent writes do not corrupt the buffer:

<<test functions>>=
def test_iolog_thread_safety():
    log = IOLog()
    errors = []

    def writer(prefix, n):
        try:
            for i in range(n):
                log.log(prefix, f"line {i}\n")
        except Exception as e:
            errors.append(e)

    threads = [
        threading.Thread(target=writer, args=("stdout", 100)),
        threading.Thread(target=writer, args=("stderr", 100)),
    ]
    for t in threads:
        t.start()
    for t in threads:
        t.join()
    assert not errors
    value = log.getvalue()
    assert value.count("stdout:") == 100
    assert value.count("stderr:") == 100
@


\section{Output stream capture}

[[StreamCapture]] wraps [[sys.stdout]] or [[sys.stderr]].
We delegate all other attribute access to the original stream so that
code checking [[sys.stdout.encoding]] or calling [[sys.stdout.isatty()]]
still works.

Why delegate via [[__getattr__]] rather than subclassing?
Because [[sys.stdout]] might be a [[TextIOWrapper]], a
[[_io.TextIOWrapper]], or any other object---we cannot know the concrete
type at import time.
Delegation works regardless of the original's type.

<<classes>>=
class StreamCapture:
    """Transparent tee wrapper for an output stream.

    Passes all writes through to the original stream while logging
    them to a shared :class:`IOLog` with the given prefix.
    """

    def __init__(self, original, name, iolog):
        self._original = original
        self._name = name
        self._iolog = iolog

    <<stream capture methods>>
@


\subsection{Writing}

Every call to [[write]] passes the text through to the original stream
\emph{and} logs it to the shared [[IOLog]].
We return the original's return value so that callers relying on it
are unaffected.

<<stream capture methods>>=
def write(self, text):
    """Write ``text`` to the original stream and log it."""
    self._iolog.log(self._name, text)
    return self._original.write(text)
@

Let's verify that writes pass through and get logged:

<<test functions>>=
def test_stream_capture_write_passes_through():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = StreamCapture(original, "stdout", log)
    cap.write("hello")
    assert original.getvalue() == "hello"

def test_stream_capture_write_logs():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = StreamCapture(original, "stderr", log)
    cap.write("error\n")
    assert "stderr: error\n" in log.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Writing multiple lines}

The [[writelines]] method handles iterables of strings, as expected by
the file-like protocol:

<<stream capture methods>>=
def writelines(self, lines):
    """Write an iterable of strings."""
    for line in lines:
        self.write(line)
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_stream_capture_writelines():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = StreamCapture(original, "stdout", log)
    cap.writelines(["a\n", "b\n"])
    assert original.getvalue() == "a\nb\n"
    assert "stdout: a\n" in log.getvalue()
    assert "stdout: b\n" in log.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Flushing and delegation}

We explicitly implement [[flush]] and delegate everything else via
[[__getattr__]]:

<<stream capture methods>>=
def flush(self):
    """Flush the original stream."""
    return self._original.flush()

def __getattr__(self, name):
    return getattr(self._original, name)
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_stream_capture_delegates_attributes():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = StreamCapture(original, "stdout", log)
    assert cap.encoding == original.encoding

def test_stream_capture_flush():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = StreamCapture(original, "stdout", log)
    cap.flush()  # should not raise
@


\section{Input stream capture}

[[InputCapture]] wraps [[sys.stdin]].
Python's built-in [[input()]] function calls [[sys.stdin.readline()]]
internally, so capturing [[readline]] is sufficient to record all
interactive input.
We also capture [[read]] for programs that read stdin in bulk
(\eg~piped input).

<<classes>>=
class InputCapture:
    """Transparent tee wrapper for an input stream.

    Passes all reads through from the original stream while logging
    the data read to a shared :class:`IOLog`.
    """

    def __init__(self, original, iolog):
        self._original = original
        self._iolog = iolog

    <<input capture methods>>
@


\subsection{Reading a line}

The [[readline]] method is the most important: it is what [[input()]]
calls under the hood.

<<input capture methods>>=
def readline(self, limit=-1):
    """Read a line from the original stream and log it."""
    line = self._original.readline(limit)
    self._iolog.log("stdin", line)
    return line
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_input_capture_readline():
    original = io.StringIO("hello\nworld\n")
    log = IOLog()
    cap = InputCapture(original, log)
    line = cap.readline()
    assert line == "hello\n"
    assert "stdin: hello\n" in log.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Bulk reading}

For programs that read all of stdin at once (\eg~piped input),
we capture [[read]] so that bulk reads are logged the same way as
line-by-line reads:

<<input capture methods>>=
def read(self, size=-1):
    """Read from the original stream and log it."""
    data = self._original.read(size)
    self._iolog.log("stdin", data)
    return data
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_input_capture_read():
    original = io.StringIO("data")
    log = IOLog()
    cap = InputCapture(original, log)
    data = cap.read()
    assert data == "data"
    assert "stdin: data" in log.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Reading multiple lines}

The [[readlines]] method returns all remaining lines as a list.
We log each line individually so they get separate prefixed entries,
matching the behavior of repeated [[readline]] calls:

<<input capture methods>>=
def readlines(self, hint=-1):
    """Read lines from the original stream and log them."""
    lines = self._original.readlines(hint)
    for line in lines:
        self._iolog.log("stdin", line)
    return lines
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_input_capture_readlines():
    original = io.StringIO("a\nb\n")
    log = IOLog()
    cap = InputCapture(original, log)
    lines = cap.readlines()
    assert lines == ["a\n", "b\n"]
    assert "stdin: a\n" in log.getvalue()
    assert "stdin: b\n" in log.getvalue()
@


\subsection{Iteration}

Programs that iterate over stdin (\eg~[[for line in sys.stdin]])
need the iterator protocol.
We delegate to [[readline]] so that each line is automatically logged:

<<input capture methods>>=
def __iter__(self):
    return self

def __next__(self):
    line = self.readline()
    if not line:
        raise StopIteration
    return line
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_input_capture_iteration():
    original = io.StringIO("a\nb\n")
    log = IOLog()
    cap = InputCapture(original, log)
    lines = list(cap)
    assert lines == ["a\n", "b\n"]
@


\subsection{Delegation}

As with [[StreamCapture]], we delegate all other attribute access to
the original stream so that code inspecting [[sys.stdin.encoding]] or
similar properties still works:

<<input capture methods>>=
def __getattr__(self, name):
    return getattr(self._original, name)
@

<<test functions>>=
def test_input_capture_delegates_attributes():
    original = io.StringIO()
    log = IOLog()
    cap = InputCapture(original, log)
    assert cap.encoding == original.encoding
